<page id="NPArtPosition" count="2/2">
    <title level="2">Nominal Phrases - Articles &amp; Demonstratives: Position and Agreement Features</title>
    <form section="np">
        <prompt id="NPArtAndDemInstruction" show="swNPArtAndDem"><span id="NPArtandDemTreespan" show="swNotPractical"><br/>Now we are ready to build the next part of the phrase structure tree.  
        </span>Key examples of nominal phrases with <span id="NPArtandDemSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span> here:</prompt>
        <textBox id="NPArtPosExample" show="swNPArtAndDem" dataItem="example"/>
        <prompt id="NPArtAndDemNoInstruction" show="swNPArtAndDemNo">Since your language does not have articles or demonstratives expressed as independent words, we do not need to determine a syntactic position for them.</prompt>
<instruction id="NPArtAndDemNoInstruction2" show="swNPArtAndDemNo">You will be instructed to add the agreement features to nouns and their affixes when we deal with agreement again in the section on possessors.</instruction>
      
       <checkboxGroup id="NPArtAndDemArtPosTable" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">
            <prompt><br/>Where does the article occur with respect to the noun? Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemArtPosBefore" dataItem="artOnlyBefore">Before it</checkbox>
             <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemArtPosAfter" dataItem="artOnlyAfter">After it</checkbox>
                <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemArtPosBoth" dataItem="artOnlyBoth">On both sides in the same nominal phrase</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemArtPosOther" dataItem="artOnlyOther">In my language, the articles may occur as follows: <textBox  id="NPArtAndDemArtPosOtherContent" dataItem="artOnlyOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
       </checkboxGroup>
       <prompt id="NPArtAndDemArtPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPArtAndDemArtAndNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the articles occur with respect to the noun in your language, or change the answer on the previous page to one that does not include articles which are written as independent words.</prompt>
       <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemArtRequiredTable" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">
          <groupName dataItem="artRequired" default="no">RNPArtAndDemArtRequired</groupName>
           <prompt><br/>Is an article required to be present in every nominal phrase (disregard possessed nouns for now)?</prompt>
          <radio id="NPArtAndDemArtRequiredNo" dataValue="no">No, an article is always optional</radio>
          <radio id="NPArtAndDemArtRequiredMass" dataValue="mass" show="swNPArtAgreementNumberYes">No, an article is optional with plural or <technicalTermRef term="ttMass"/> nouns, but is required with singular nouns</radio>
          <radio id="NPArtAndDemArtRequiredYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, an article is always required</radio>
     </radioGroup>          
 
       <checkboxGroup id="NPArtAndDemDemPosTable" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">
            <prompt><br/>Where does the demonstrative occur with respect to the noun? Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemDemPosBefore" dataItem="demOnlyBefore">Before it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemDemPosAfter" dataItem="demOnlyAfter">After it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemDemPosBoth" dataItem="demOnlyBoth">On both sides in the same nominal phrase</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemDemPosOther" dataItem="demOnlyOther">In my language, the demonstratives may occur as follows: <textBox  id="NPArtAndDemDemPosOtherContent" dataItem="demOnlyOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
       </checkboxGroup>
       <prompt id="NPArtAndDemDemPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPArtAndDemDemAndNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the demonstratives occur with respect to the noun in your language, or change the answer on the previous page to one that does not include demonstratives which are written as independent words.</prompt>
       <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemDemRequiredTable" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">
            <groupName dataItem="demRequired" default="no">RNPArtAndDemDemRequired</groupName>
           <prompt><br/>Is a demonstrative required to be present in every nominal phrase (disregard possessed nouns for now)?</prompt>
            <radio id="NPArtAndDemDemRequiredNo" dataValue="no">No, a demonstrative is always optional</radio>
            <radio id="NPArtAndDemDemRequiredMass" dataValue="mass" show="swNPDemAgreementNumberYes">No, a demonstrative is optional with plural or <technicalTermRef term="ttMass"/> nouns, but is required with singular nouns</radio>
            <radio id="NPArtAndDemDemRequiredYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, a demonstrative is always required</radio>
       </radioGroup>
        
        <radioGroup id="NPDemClassifierSpecificTable" show="swOTClassifierSpecificAndNPArtAndDemDem">
            <groupName dataItem="classifierPresentDem" default="no">RNPDemClassifierPresent</groupName>
            <prompt><br/>Looking at the examples, are classifiers used in these nominal phrases with a demonstrative?</prompt>
            <radio id="NPDemClassifierPresentYes"  dataValue="yes">Yes, a classifier is required in all nominal phrases which contain a demonstrative</radio>
            <radio id="NPDemClassifierPresentSome" dataValue="some">A classifier is present in some nominal phrases which contain a demonstrative, but is not required in all of them</radio>
            <radio id="NPDemClassifierPresentNo" dataValue="no">No, a classifier is never used in this type of nominal phrase</radio>
        </radioGroup>
        <checkboxGroup id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPos" show="swOTClassifierSpecificAndNPArtAndDemDemAndNPDemClassifierPresentYesOrSome">
            <prompt><br/>Looking at the examples, where do the classifiers occur with respect to the demonstrative and the noun?  Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosBeforeBoth"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosBeforeBoth">First, before both the demonstrative and the noun</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosAfterBoth"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosAfterBoth">Last, after both the noun and the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosAfterDemBeforeN"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosAfterDemBeforeN">After the demonstrative but before the noun</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosAfterNBeforeDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosAfterNBeforeDem">After the noun but before the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosPrefixDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosPrefixDem">As a prefix on the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosSuffixDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosSuffixDem">As a suffix on the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosOther"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosOther">In my language, the classifiers may occur in the following position: <textBox  id="NPClassifierSpecificDemPosOtherContent" dataItem="classifierSpecificDemPosOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
        </checkboxGroup>
        <prompt id="NPDemClassifierSpecificPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPDemClassifierPresentYesOrSomeAndNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the classifiers occur with respect to the demonstrative and the noun in your language, or change your answer above to “No, a classifier is never used in this type of nominal phrase”.</prompt>
        
       <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">
            <groupName dataItem="artBothCooccur" default="different">RNPArtAndDemBoth</groupName>
            <prompt><br/>Do articles and demonstratives co-occur in the same nominal phrase?</prompt>
            <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNo" dataValue="no">No, they occur in the same position, like in English</radio>
          <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurDiff" dataValue="different">No, but they occur in different positions with respect to the noun</radio>
          <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, both can be present in a single nominal phrase</radio>
       </radioGroup>
       <checkboxGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurNo">
          <prompt><br/>Where does the demonstrative or article occur with respect to the noun?</prompt>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosBefore" dataItem="demOrArtPosBefore">Before it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosAfter" dataItem="demOrArtPosAfter">After it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosBoth" dataItem="demOrArtPosBoth">On both sides in the same nominal phrase</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosOther" dataItem="demOrArtPosOther">In my language, the demonstrative or article may occur as follows: <textBox  id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosOtherContent" dataItem="demOrArtPosOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
       </checkboxGroup>
       <prompt id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoAndNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the articles and demonstratives occur with respect to the noun in your language.</prompt>
 
 
       <checkboxGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYes">
          <prompt><br/>Where does the demonstrative occur with respect to the noun? Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosBefore" dataItem="demAndArtDemBefore">Before it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosAfter" dataItem="demAndArtDemAfter">After it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosBoth" dataItem="demAndArtDemBoth">On both sides in the same nominal phrase</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosOther" dataItem="demAndArtDemOther">In my language, the demonstratives may occur as follows: <textBox  id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosOtherContent" dataItem="demAndArtDemOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
       </checkboxGroup>
       <prompt id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesAndDemPosNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the demonstratives occur with respect to the noun in your language.</prompt>
       
       <checkboxGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYes">
          <prompt><br/>Where does the article occur with respect to the noun? Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosBefore" dataItem="demAndArtArtBefore">Before it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosAfter" dataItem="demAndArtArtAfter">After it</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosBoth" dataItem="demAndArtArtBoth">On both sides in the same nominal phrase</checkbox>
          <checkbox id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosOther" dataItem="demAndArtArtOther">In my language, the articles may occur as follows: <textBox  id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosOtherContent" dataItem="demAndArtArtOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
       </checkboxGroup>
       <prompt id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesAndArtPosNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the articles occur with respect to the noun in your language.</prompt>
       <instruction id="NPArtDemEitherSideRestrictedInstruction" show="swNPArtDemEitherSideRestricted">In the lexicon, mark those which can only occur before the noun with the feature <feature>DP-initial</feature> and those which can only occur after the noun with the feature <feature>DP-final</feature>.  Do not enter either feature on any articles or demonstratives which can occur on either side.</instruction>
       <instruction id="NPArtEitherSideRestrictedInstruction" show="swNPArtEitherSideRestricted">In the lexicon, mark those which can only occur before the noun with the feature <feature>DP-initial</feature> and those which can only occur after the noun with the feature <feature>DP-final</feature>.  Do not enter either feature on any articles which can occur on either side.</instruction>
       <instruction id="NPDemEitherSideRestrictedInstruction" show="swNPDemEitherSideRestricted">In the lexicon, mark those which can only occur before the noun with the feature <feature>DP-initial</feature> and those which can only occur after the noun with the feature <feature>DP-final</feature>.  Do not enter either feature on any demonstratives which can occur on either side.</instruction>
       <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoRequiredTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurNo">
                <groupName dataItem="demOrArtRequired" default="no">RNPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoRequired</groupName>
           <prompt><br/>Is a demonstrative or an article required to be present in every nominal phrase (disregard possessed nouns for now)?</prompt>
                <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoRequiredNo" dataValue="no">No, the presence of a demonstrative or an article is always optional</radio>
                <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoRequiredMass" dataValue="mass" show="swNPArtOrDemAgreementNumberYes">No, a demonstrative or an article is optional with plural or <technicalTermRef term="ttMass"/> nouns, but is required with singular nouns</radio>
                <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurNoRequiredYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, either a demonstrative or an article is always required</radio>
            </radioGroup>
          
          <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemRequiredTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYes">
             <groupName dataItem="demAndArtDemRequired" default="no">RNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemRequired</groupName>
              <prompt><br/>Is a demonstrative required to be present in every nominal phrase (disregard possessed nouns for now)?</prompt>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemRequiredNo" dataValue="no">No, a demonstrative is always optional</radio>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemRequiredMass" dataValue="mass" show="swNPDemAgreementNumberYes">No, a demonstrative is optional with plural or <technicalTermRef term="ttMass"/> nouns, but is required with singular nouns</radio>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesDemRequiredYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, a demonstrative is always required</radio>
          </radioGroup>
          <radioGroup id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtRequiredTable" show="swNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYes">
             <groupName dataItem="demAndArtArtRequired" default="no">RNPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtRequired</groupName>
              <prompt><br/>Is an article required to be present in every nominal phrase (disregard possessed nouns for now)?</prompt>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtRequiredNo" dataValue="no">No, an article is always optional</radio>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtRequiredMass" dataValue="mass" show="swNPArtAgreementNumberYes">No, an article is optional with plural or <technicalTermRef term="ttMass"/> nouns, but is required with singular nouns</radio>
             <radio id="NPArtAndDemBothCooccurYesArtRequiredYes" dataValue="yes">Yes, an article is always required</radio>
          </radioGroup>
        
        <radioGroup id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificTable" show="swOTClassifierSpecificAndNPArtAndDemBoth">
            <groupName dataItem="classifierPresentDemBoth" default="no">RNPDemBothClassifierPresent</groupName>
            <prompt><br/>Looking at the examples, are classifiers used in these nominal phrases with a demonstrative?</prompt>
            <radio id="NPDemBothClassifierPresentYes"  dataValue="yes">Yes, a classifier is required in all nominal phrases which contain a demonstrative</radio>
            <radio id="NPDemBothClassifierPresentSome" dataValue="some">A classifier is present in some nominal phrases which contain a demonstrative, but is not required in all of them</radio>
            <radio id="NPDemBothClassifierPresentNo" dataValue="no">No, a classifier is never used in this type of nominal phrase</radio>
        </radioGroup>
        <checkboxGroup id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPos" show="swOTClassifierSpecificAndNPArtAndDemBothAndNPDemBothClassifierPresentYesOrSome">
            <prompt><br/>Looking at the examples, where do the classifiers occur with respect to the demonstrative and the noun?  Check all options that are correct for your language</prompt>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosBeforeBoth"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosBeforeBoth">First, before both the demonstrative and the noun</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosAfterBoth"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosAfterBoth">Last, after both the noun and the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosAfterDemBeforeN"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosAfterDemBeforeN">After the demonstrative but before the noun</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosAfterNBeforeDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosAfterNBeforeDem">After the noun but before the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosPrefixDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosPrefixDem">As a prefix on the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosSuffixDem"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosSuffixDem">As a suffix on the demonstrative</checkbox>
            <checkbox id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosOther"  dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosOther">In my language, the classifiers may occur in the following position: <textBox  id="NPClassifierSpecificDemBothPosOtherContent" dataItem="classifierSpecificDemBothPosOther" rows="2"/></checkbox>
        </checkboxGroup>
        <prompt id="NPDemBothClassifierSpecificPosNoCheckPrompt" show="swNPDemBothClassifierPresentYesOrSomeAndNoCheck">WARNING: You need to check at least one box to describe where the classifiers occur with respect to the demonstrative and the noun in your language, or change your answer above to “No, a classifier is never used in this type of nominal phrase”.</prompt>
        
        <instruction id="NPArtAgreementNumberInstruction" show="swNPArtAgreementNumberYes">
To handle the number agreement, in the lexicon:
<ul>
                <li>Mark the articles that can only go with singular nouns with the feature <feature>singular</feature>.</li>
                <li>Mark the articles that can only go with plural nouns with the feature <feature>plural</feature>.</li>
                <li>Do not add any feature for number agreement to ones like <example>the</example> in English which can go with either singular or plural nouns.</li>
                <li>If your language makes a further distinction for dual marking, add the feature <feature>dual</feature> to the appropriate articles.
                </li>
</ul>
            </instruction>
        <instruction id="NPDemAgreementNumberInstruction" show="swNPDemAgreementNumberYes">
            To handle the number agreement, in the lexicon:
            <ul>
                <li>Mark the demonstratives that can only go with singular nouns with the feature <feature>singular</feature>.</li>
                <li>Mark the demonstratives that can only go with plural nouns with the feature <feature>plural</feature>.</li>
                <li>Do not add any feature for number agreement to any which can go with either singular or plural nouns.</li>
                <li>If your language makes a further distinction for dual marking, add the feature <feature>dual</feature> to the appropriate demonstratives.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </instruction>
        <instruction id="NPAgreementNumberInstruction" show="swNPAgreementNumberYes">
                We will assume that all nouns are singular by default.  Therefore, only the plural nouns need to be marked.  In the lexicon:
<ul>
                <li>Add the feature <feature>plural</feature> to any affixes which can be added to a noun to make it plural.</li>
                <li>Also, add the feature <feature>plural</feature> to any nouns which are inherently plural (such as <example>scissors</example> or <example>pants</example> in English), or exceptionally don’t take an affix.</li>
                <li>Any nouns which do not make a distinction between singular and plural forms, such as <example>deer</example> in English, need to have two entries in the lexicon, one marked with the feature <feature>plural</feature> and the other for singular (which can be explicitly marked or allowed to use the default).  The parser will choose the correct form based on the context.</li>
                <li id="NPArtDemMassSpan" show="swNPArtDemMassYes">All mass nouns need to have the feature <feature>mass</feature> so that <span id="NPArtOnlyMassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">an article</span><span id="NPDemOnlyMassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">a demonstrative</span><span id="NPArtAndDemMassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">an article or demonstrative</span> will not be required.</li>
            </ul>
        </instruction>
        <instruction id="NPArtAgreementAnimacyInstruction" show="swNPArtAgreementAnimacyYes">
To handle animacy agreement:
<ul>
                <li>Mark the <span id="NPArtOnlyAnimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span>
<span id="NPDemOnlyAnimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemAnimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> that can only go with animate nouns with the feature <feature>animate</feature>.</li>
                <li>Mark the <span id="NPArtOnlyInanimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyInanimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemInanimateSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> that can only go with inanimate nouns with the feature <feature>-animate</feature>.</li>
                <li>Do not add any animacy agreement feature to those which can go with either animate or inanimate nouns.</li>
				<li>If your language makes the further distinction between human and nonhuman, add the feature <feature>human</feature> to the <span id="NPArtOnlyHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> that can only go with human nouns and add the feature <feature>-human</feature> to the <span id="NPArtOnlyNonHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span>
<span id="NPDemOnlyNonHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemNonHumanSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> that can only go with nonhuman nouns.</li>
            </ul>
We will assume that all (common) nouns are inanimate and nonhuman by default. Therefore, only the animate nouns need to be marked.  In the lexicon, add the feature <feature>animate</feature> to any animate nouns, such as <example>person</example>, <example>people</example>, <example>crowd</example>, <example>animal</example>, and names of types of animals which are not proper names.  Also add the feature <feature>human</feature> as appropriate if your language makes the further distinction between human and nonhuman nouns.  (Proper names will be dealt with in <section number="6">Proper Names</section>.)
</instruction>
		<instruction id="NPArtAgreementGenderInstruction" show="swNPArtAgreementGenderYes">
Add the gender features <feature>masculine</feature>, <feature>feminine</feature>, <feature>neuter</feature> to any <span id="NPArtOnlyGenderSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyGenderSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemGenderSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles or demonstratives</span> that can only go with that type of noun.  Do not add any gender agreement feature to those which can go with either masculine or feminine nouns.<br/>
            <br/>
We will assume that all nouns are masculine by default.  Therefore, only the feminine and neuter nouns need to be marked.  In the lexicon:
<ul>
                <li>Add the feature <feature>feminine</feature> to any affixes which can be added to a noun to make it feminine.  Add the feature <feature>neuter</feature> to any affixes which can be added to a noun to make it neuter.</li>
                <li>Also, add the feature <feature>feminine</feature> to any nouns which are inherently feminine, or exceptionally don’t take an affix.  Similarly, add the feature <feature>neuter</feature> to any nouns which are inherently neuter, or exceptionally don’t take an affix.</li>
                <li>Any nouns which do have the same form for both masculine and feminine, but which can take different forms of the <span id="NPArtOnlyGender2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span>
<span id="NPDemOnlyGender2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemGender2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> based on gender need to have two entries in the lexicon, one marked with the feature <feature>feminine</feature> and the other for masculine (which can be explicitly marked or allowed to use the default).  The parser will choose the correct form based on the context.</li>
			</ul>
        </instruction>
		<instruction id="NPArtAgreementClassInstruction" show="swNPArtAgreementClassYes">
To handle class marking and agreement:
<ul>
   <li>It is most likely the case that the same affixes that mark the class number or type on <span id="NPArtOnlyClass1Span" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyClass1Span" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemClass1Span" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> (and possibly adjectives too) are also used on nouns.  If this is the case in your language, the appropriate class feature should already have been added to the affixes in <section number="1.">Overall Typology Questions - Noun Classes and Classifiers</section>, so all the words will automatically come from the morphological parser with the class number or type marked.</li>
   <li>Any cases where <span id="NPArtOnlyClass2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyClass2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemClass2Span" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles, demonstratives</span> or nouns do not have an affix which marks the class will require marking of the class feature on the particular lexical item in the lexicon.   Mark the <span id="NPArtOnlyClassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemArt">articles</span><span id="NPDemOnlyClassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemDem">demonstratives</span><span id="NPArtAndDemClassSpan" show="swNPArtAndDemBoth">articles and demonstratives</span> that can only go with a particular class with the feature <feature>class_##</feature>, where ## is replaced by a number between 1 and 25.  Alternatively, these can be marked with one of the class type features discussed in <section number="1.">Overall Typology Questions - Noun Classes and Classifiers</section>.</li>
            </ul>
        </instruction>
        <br/>
